    {
      "id": "1kwutiwar",
      "questionNumber": 14,
      "questionText": "If $${({x^2} + {y^2})^2} = xy$$, then $${{dy} \\over {dx}}$$ is ",
      "options": [
        "$${{y + 4x({x^2} + {y^2})} \\over {4y({x^2} + {y^2}) - x}}$$",
        "$${{y - 4x({x^2} + {y^2})} \\over {x + 4({x^2} + {y^2})}}$$",
        "$${{y - 4x({x^2} + {y^2})} \\over {4y({x^2} + {y^2}) - x}}$$",
        "$${{4y({x^2} + {y^2}) - x} \\over {y - 4x({x^2} + {y^2})}}$$"
      ],
      "correctOption": 2,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Mathematics",
      "topic": "General",
      "difficulty": "Medium",
      "solution": "<p>We will differentiate both sides of the equation implicitly with respect to  $$x$$. </p>\n\n<p>$$2({x^2} + {y^2}) \\cdot (2x + 2y \\cdot {{dy} \\over {dx}}) = y + x \\cdot {{dy} \\over {dx}}$$</p>\n\n<p>Expanding the equation, we get:</p>\n\n<p>$$4x({x^2} + {y^2}) + 4y({x^2} + {y^2}) \\cdot {{dy} \\over {dx}} = y + x \\cdot {{dy} \\over {dx}}$$</p>\n\n<p>Now, isolate $${{dy} \\over {dx}}$$: </p>\n\n<p>$$4y({x^2} + {y^2}) \\cdot {{dy} \\over {dx}} - x \\cdot {{dy} \\over {dx}} = y - 4x({x^2} + {y^2})$$</p>\n\n<p>$${{dy} \\over {dx}} \\cdot [4y({x^2} + {y^2}) - x] = y - 4x({x^2} + {y^2})$$</p>\n\n<p>Finally, we obtain the derivative:</p>\n\n<p>$${{dy} \\over {dx}} = {{y - 4x({x^2} + {y^2})} \\over {4y({x^2} + {y^2}) - x}}$$</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the correct answer is <strong>Option C</strong>: $${{y - 4x({x^2} + {y^2})} \\over {4y({x^2} + {y^2}) - x}}$$</p>",
      "section": "Sec 3",
      "instruction": ""
    },
